reasoning: First off, Alphabet (GOOG) largely sits outside my circle of competence. I don’t fully grasp the intricacies of search algorithms and online ad-pricing the way I understand bottling Coca-Cola or running a railroad. That said, it’s clear Google enjoys a formidable moat: network effects in search, massive data assets and brand power give it durable pricing power. Management appears capable – steering huge cash flows into prudent bets like YouTube and AI – and the balance sheet is fortress-like, generating consistent earnings with minimal debt. Unfortunately, with zero valuation data here, I can’t determine a margin of safety. Regulatory headwinds and rapid tech shifts add long-term risk, and without a price tag versus intrinsic value, I’m stuck. Compared to opportunities like Coca-Cola or Apple in my portfolio, I’d rather sit on cash until the picture clears. Until I see the numbers that let me calculate intrinsic value, my signal is neutral – there just isn’t enough here for a yes or a no.
